{"pageProps":{"tutorial":{"title":"MongoDB Schema Design","slug":"mongodb-schema-design","subject":"MongoDB","category":"NoSQL Database","level":"Intermediate","estimated_read_time":"30 mins","prerequisites":["Introduction to NoSQL"],"learning_objectives":["Embedding vs Referencing","One-to-One","One-to-Many","Many-to-Many"],"theory":"Schema design in MongoDB relies on the access patterns of your application. The key decision is always Embed (nesting data) vs Reference (linking data). Embed is better for read performance; Reference is better for data consistency and large datasets.","syntax":"N/A","examples":[{"code":"// Embedded (One-to-Few)\n{\n  name: \"Alice\",\n  addresses: [ { city: \"NY\" }, { city: \"LA\" } ]\n}\n\n// Referenced (One-to-Many)\n{ name: \"Alice\", address_ids: [101, 102] }","output":"Modeling choices","explanation":"Addresses are usually embedded because they belong to the user and are viewed with the user."}],"common_mistakes":[{"mistake":"Deep nesting","correction":"Don't nest too deep. Queries become complex and document size limits hit.","example":"User -> Posts -> Comments -> Likes -> User (Circular/Deep)"}],"interview_questions":[{"question":"When should you use referencing over embedding?","answer":"When the 'many' side is large (unbounded growth), frequently updated individually, or accessed typically without the parent.","difficulty":"Advanced"}],"practice_problems":[],"real_world_use_cases":[],"exam_notes":["Design for Usage (Read/Write patterns), not for SQL normalization."],"summary":"Good schema design is critical. In NoSQL, data structures are optimized for specific application queries.","order":34},"courseTutorials":[{"slug":"database-introduction","path":"content/mongodb/database-introduction.json","title":"Introduction to Databases","category":"NoSQL Database","subject":"MongoDB","description":"","order":1},{"slug":"nosql-introduction","path":"content/mongodb/nosql-introduction.json","title":"Introduction to NoSQL","category":